# testing-fault-test-placeholder-must-go-red — History

## v1.1.0 (2026-06-19)

**Changed by:** Re-plan of GitHub issue #184 (Odysseus e2e NATS crash-reconnect placeholder test) after a reviewer NOGO on the v1.0.0 plan.
**Verification:** unverified (still planning discipline — the re-plan was never executed; no code run, no CI observed)

### What changed

- Added the durable lesson that the fix for an "unverified core assumption" review finding is to READ THE ACTUAL CLIENT/LIBRARY SOURCE, not to add hedging prose. Cited `natsConnection_ConnectTo` (libnats DEFAULT options = auto-reconnect ON: `AllowReconnect=true`, `MaxReconnect=60`, `ReconnectWait=2s`) which converted the #1 risk from "assumed" to "verified can-go-GREEN".
- Added the lesson that a recovery test must be shown able to go BOTH RED and GREEN — proving only RED is necessary-but-insufficient.
- Added the scope-DOWN lesson: dropping topology T4 (a documented-broken substrate) deleted an entire class of defects (the self-contradictory compose path M1, the port-override bug substrate M3, an over-generalized persistence rationale). Skip broken substrates explicitly with the bug cited inline.
- Added the pre-existing-blocker lesson: reading code to fix one finding surfaced that the T1 launcher (`start_myrmidon_bg`) pointed at a non-existent `main.py` while the component is C++ (`main.cpp`) — a verification step that depends on a broken harness is "aspirational verification".
- Added the DRY/divergence lesson: reference EXACT exported variables with `${VAR:?}` (fail-loud) instead of duplicating defaults like `${PORT:-18222}`.
- Added 5 new Failed Attempts / anti-pattern rows.
- Added reviewer-risk refinements to Results & Parameters (libnats version-dependent defaults, JetStream store-lock/port-rebind race, double `run_task_lifecycle` idempotency, derived 90s timeout budget, pixi-wraps-runner unconfirmed).
- Added `history` frontmatter field; bumped version 1.0.0 -> 1.1.0 (MINOR); date stays 2026-06-19.

### Why

The v1.0.0 plan was reviewed NOGO because it answered an "unverified core assumption" finding
with more prose rather than reading the client source, claimed multi-topology (T1+T4) support
where T4 rests on a documented bug, shipped a code block contradicted by a trailing prose Note,
and relied on a harness helper (myrmidon launcher) that could never pass on a clean run. The
re-plan corrected all four by reading the actual source, scoping to the one working topology (T1),
and validating helpers. The transferable lesson — verify assumptions by reading source, prove
both RED and GREEN, scope down off broken substrates, and never let verification depend on an
unopened/broken helper — is the durable value captured in this amendment.

